  urldate = {2022-02-15},
  abstract = {\emph{Context.{$<$}i/{$>$} Previous theoretical works on planet formation around low-mass stars have often been limited to large planets and individual systems. As current surveys routinely detect planets down to terrestrial size in these systems, models have shifted toward a more holistic approach that reflects their diverse architectures.\emph{Aims.{$<$}i/{$>$} Here, we investigate planet formation around low-mass stars and identify differences in the statistical distribution of modeled planets. We compare the synthetic planet populations to observed exoplanets and we discuss the identified trends.\emph{Methods.{$<$}i/{$>$} We used the Generation III Bern global model of planet formation and evolution to calculate synthetic populations, while varying the central star from Solar-like stars to ultra-late M dwarfs. This model includes planetary migration, \emph{N{$<$}i/{$>$}-body interactions between embryos, accretion of planetesimals and gas, and the long-term contraction and loss of the gaseous atmospheres.\emph{Results.{$<$}i/{$>$} We find that temperate, Earth-sized planets are most frequent around early M dwarfs (0.3 \emph{M{$<$}i/{$>$}\textsubscript{{$\odot<$}sub/{$>$}--0.5 \emph{M{$<$}i/{$>$}\textsubscript{{$\odot<$}sub/{$>$}) and that they are more rare for Solar-type stars and late M dwarfs. The planetary mass distribution does not linearly scale with the disk mass. The reason behind this is attributed to the emergence of giant planets for \emph{M{$<$}i/{$>$}\textsubscript{{$\star<$}sub/{$>$} {$\geq$} 0.5 \emph{M{$<$}i/{$>$}\textsubscript{{$\odot<$}sub/{$>$}, which leads to the ejection of smaller planets. Given a linear scaling of the disk mass with stellar mass, the formation of Earth-like planets is limited by the available amount of solids for ultra-late M dwarfs. For \emph{M{$<$}i/{$>$}\textsubscript{{$\star<$}sub/{$>$} {$\geq$} 0.3 \emph{M{$<$}i/{$>$}\textsubscript{{$\odot<$}sub/{$>$}, however, there is sufficient mass in the majority of systems, leading to a similar amount of Exo-Earths going from M to G dwarfs. In contrast, the number of super-Earths and larger planets increases monotonically with stellar mass. We further identify a regime of disk parameters that reproduces observed M-dwarf systems such as TRAPPIST-1. However, giant planets around late M dwarfs, such as GJ 3512b, only form when type I migration is substantially reduced.\emph{Conclusions.{$<$}i/{$>$} We are able to quantify the stellar mass dependence of multi-planet systems using global simulations of planet formation and evolution. The results fare well in comparison to current observational data and predict trends that can be tested with future observations.}}}}}}}}}}}}}}}}}}},
