}\textsubscript{p{$<$}sub/{$>$} = 2, 3, 5 \emph{R{$<$}i/{$>$}\textsubscript{J{$<$}sub/{$>$}, which is in line with the statistical results obtained for more evolved systems from other direct imaging surveys. These values are obtained under the assumption that extinction from circumstellar and circumplanetary material does not affect the companion signal, but we show the potential impact these factors might have on the detectability of forming objects.\emph{Conclusions.{$<$}i/{$>$} The NaCo-ISPY data confirm that massive bright planets accreting at high rates are rare. More powerful instruments with better sensitivity in the near- to mid-infrared are likely required to unveil the wealth of forming planets sculpting the observed disk substructures.}}}}}}}}}}}}}}}},
