  urldate = {2023-11-15},
  abstract = {WASP-107b is a warm (\,{\textasciitilde}\,740 K) transiting planet with a Neptune-like mass of\,{\textasciitilde}\,30.5 M{$\oplus$} and Jupiter-like radius of\,{\textasciitilde}\,0.94 RJ 1,2 whose extended atmosphere is eroding 3. Previous observations showed evidence for water vapour and a thick high-altitude condensate layer in WASP-107b's atmosphere 4,5. Recently, photochemically produced sulphur dioxide (SO2) was detected in the atmosphere of a hot (\,{\textasciitilde}\,1,200 K) Saturn-mass planet from transmission spectroscopy near 4.05 {$\mu$}m 6,7, but for temperatures below\,{\textasciitilde}\,1,000 K sulphur is predicted to preferably form sulphur allotropes instead of SO2 8,9,10. Here we report the 9{$\sigma$}-detection of two fundamental vibration bands of SO2, at 7.35 {$\mu$}m and 8.69 {$\mu$}m, in the transmission spectrum of WASP-107b using the Mid-Infrared Instrument (MIRI) of the JWST. This discovery establishes WASP-107b as the second irradiated exoplanet with confirmed photochemistry, extending the temperature range of exoplanets exhibiting detected photochemistry from\,{\textasciitilde}\,1,200 K down to\,{\textasciitilde}\,740 K. Additionally, our spectral analysis reveals the presence of silicate clouds, which are strongly favoured (\,{\textasciitilde}\,7{$\sigma$}) over simpler cloud setups. Furthermore, water is detected (\,{\textasciitilde}\,12{$\sigma$}), but methane is not. These findings provide evidence of disequilibrium chemistry and indicate a dynamically active atmosphere with a super-solar metallicity.},
