  abstract = {ABSTRACT             We study the Roman~sensitivity to exoplanets in the Habitable Zone (HZ). The Roman~efficiency for detecting habitable planets is maximized for three classes of planetary microlensing events with close caustic topologies. (a) The events with the lens distances of Dl {$\greaterequivlnt$} 7~kpc, the host lens masses of \$M\_\{{\textbackslash}rm h\}{\textbackslash}gtrsim 0.6{\textbackslash}, \{{\textbackslash}rm M\}\_\{{\textbackslash}odot \}\$. By assuming Jupiter-mass planets in the HZs, these events have q {$\lessequivlnt$} 0.001 and d {$\greaterequivlnt$} 0.17 (q is their mass ratio and d is the projected planet-host distance on the sky plane normalized to the Einstein radius). The events with primary lenses, \$M\_\{{\textbackslash}rm h\} {\textbackslash}lesssim 0.1 {\textbackslash}, \{{\textbackslash}rm M\}\_\{{\textbackslash}odot \}\$, while their lens systems are either (b) close to the observer with Dl {$\lessequivlnt$} 1~kpc or (c) close to the Galactic bulge, Dl {$\greaterequivlnt$} 7~kpc. For Jupiter-mass planets in the HZs of the primary lenses, the events in these two classes have q {$\greaterequivlnt$} 0.01, d {$\lessequivlnt$} 0.04. The events in the class (a) make larger caustics. By simulating planetary microlensing events detectable by Roman,~we conclude that the Roman~efficiencies for detecting Earth- and Jupiter-mass planets in the Optimistic HZs (OHZs, which is the region between [0.5, 2] au around a Sun-like star) are 0.01 and \$5\{\{{\textbackslash} {\textbackslash}rm per{\textbackslash} cent\}\}\$, respectively. If we assume that one exoplanet orbits each microlens in microlensing events detectable by Roman~(i.e. {$\sim$}27\,000),~this telescope has the potential to detect 35 exoplanets with the projected planet-host distances in the OHZs with only one having a mass {$\lessequivlnt$}10M{$\oplus$}. According to the simulation, 27 of these exoplanets are actually in the OHZs.},
